[1] UK (Scotland), swan, H5
Date: Wed 5 Apr 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: BBC Online, 5 Apr 2006 [edited]
<http://news.bbc.co.uk/go/pr/fr/-/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/4881526.stm>


Bird flu confirmed in dead swan
-----------------------------------
Preliminary tests have found the H5 avian flu in a sample from a swan found
dead in Fife, health officials have revealed. The exact strain of the virus
is not yet known, but tests were continuing, and further results were
expected on Thursday [6 Apr 2006]. The Scottish Executive said the area was
being sealed off.

If the disease is confirmed as the deadly H5N1 strain, there may be further
restrictions put in place.

An executive spokesman said: "In accordance with a recent EU decision, the
Scottish Executive is putting in place a protection zone of a minimum of 3
km radius and a surveillance zone of 10 km. Keepers of birds in the
protection zone are being instructed to isolate their birds from wild birds
by taking them indoors where ever possible." Measures to restrict the
movement of poultry, eggs and poultry products from these zones will be
brought into effect immediately. Officials stressed that there was no
reason for public health concern.

Chief Veterinary Officer for Scotland Charles Milne said: "Whilst disease
has yet to be confirmed, this is an important development. "Bird keepers
outside the protection zone should redouble their efforts to prepare for
bringing their birds indoors if that becomes necessary. "They must also
review their biosecurity measures to ensure that all possible precautions
have been taken."

Ruth Watkins is a retired clinical virologist who told NEWS 24 about the
distinctions in the virus. "The H5N1 highly pathogenic virus has come
across Asia from China and into Europe, with birds fleeing the very very
cold conditions in central Europe, and it's been found in wild birds in
many European countries, particularly where ducks and geese and so on have
congregated in wetland areas. Of course, it's possible it might also be
brought by a wild birds into the United Kingdom. But so far, there's been
only one incident where turkeys that actually were enclosed in a house in
southern France were infected: they were slaughtered, and it didn't spread
any further. There's been one incident, I believe, in Denmark, where one
mallard was positive for it on a farm where I believe there were about 500
other birds of various kinds who were all slaughtered, and none other was
found to be infected. So basically, it sounds to me like sensible
precautionary measures have been taken, and I presume the specimen is at
Weybridge and they'll be doing a preliminary chain reaction and sequencing
it, and they'll be able to say, probably tomorrow [6 Apr 2006], definitely
whether or not it's the highly pathogenic strain."

